Unfortunately, we must accept this ultimatum if we are to maintain this coalition. The Nazis and Communists are waiting in the wings for us to fail, ready to pounce upon the instability that would result from a breakup of the governing coalition.

The industrialists and small business owners are furious at our betrayal, as are a good portion of our membership throughout the rightist factions, which are threatening a full on seccession from the party. Our loss is the DNVP's gain, and even the NSDAP, who heavy industry see as the only parties willing to stand up to the <span style="color: #E3000F;">socialists</span>.

The workers, at least, are pleased at the government's course of action, although they attribute most of the credit to the <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span>.

Still, this has deradicalized the workers away from the extremes at both ends of the political spectrum, as they see the parties of the government as acting in their interest in this time of crisis.

The <span style="color: #E3000F;">**SPD**</span> is pleasantly surprised at our backing of their increase in the tax burden upon the rich, and we have seen a substantial improvement in relations and decrease in coalition tensions as a result.

@compromise
